snippet.textDisplay: I'm a huge huge Star Wars fan I've always been and will be a fan. I've seen all 3 of the sequel films in the cinema. But I came out devastated or hugely disappointed every time. All 3 movies had incredible music by John Williams who is a GOD! I love his work! That's about all the good things they have in common. This film was the most beautiful out of all 9 films I loved General Pryde finally a capable leader who will give you chills as Tarkin did. But overall I didn't like the cinematography or the VFX work. I don't think I've ever felt like I've had a problem with cinematography in a quote and quote professional Hollywood film. I was just sad and frustrated. I've felt that J.J. Abrams was an incompetent writer/director.  Which made me even more depressed, because I know he is a huge fan who has poured his heart and soul into this film. Before and during film school I watched J. J.'s lecture that he delivered in a TED talk years before Disney bought Lucasarts. In this lecture, he spoke about his love of Star Wars among other things. Anyways going back to the film. The film was a narrative disaster. It was lacking any creativity and craftsmanship. He took the rules of writing and threw it all out of the window. Within the first 2-3 minutes, my friend wanted to bet me that Kylo and Rey will end up tag-teaming against Palpatine. To which I responded with a no, because I didn't want to bet on a sure thing. We both knew ahead of time how it will and the same goes for the kissing. I think almost any film which has an ending this predictable has a failed script at least in some respects. Giving away Palpatine in the first minute is a huge-huge problem, both in the film and its marketing material. The film lacks almost any sort of real obstacle's to get to Palpatine I didn't doubt for a second that both of them would get to him. The film is full of meaningless sidequests without any real obstacles. Like how C3PO-s memory wipe had no real sense of obstacle it was just way to drag the story onwards without real dramatic progression. They never have to think hard, fight hard, suffer to get anything, all they need to do is travel to places and everything will fall into their laps. The way death is handled here (too) just makes it really hard to take any death scenes seriously. But anyway the 1 scene that showed me total incompetence as a writer and director is when they flew to that gorgeous ice place (planet?).  They go into a small hole and dock the ship so that R2-D2 can download an intel. They have downloaded the Intel and that's when the imperial's start to appear in the whole. This does not create suspense!!! If they wanted to create real suspense all they had to do without draging the scene out. Is to change the order of the clips in the editing timeline. If they're still nowhere near close to downloading the intel (which didn't seem to crucial it should've felt more crucial) when TIE fighters are already close by then there would've been a real sense of suspense. And have them escape in the last minute. And then J.J. also broke (after breaking a bunch of writing rules) all the in-universe rules that were set up by the previous films.  I hope he will make something great again like Super8, but this was disheartening. I love the channel keep it up, it's so much fun even if we don't agree on this film! Thanks for all your hard work!

snippet.textDisplay:
I just finished watching it.

Yikes.

This entire movie was one big deus ex machina, full of events that just so happened perfectly to drive the story forward. The only, sole purpose for its inception was to repair any mistakes that started in the force awakens and the last jedi. In this regard, it did well.

As a movie, it was trash. Imo. It moved wayyyy too fast, and never gve you time to stop and process what just went on. It is a never ending sequence of events with no pauses in the action to breathe a little.

Rey is still overpowered as fuck. Literally mind tricking a PAIR of troopers (Usually takes one YEARS to master it on one person), she literally just grabs a flying ship out of thin air while it's moving... Master Yoda only barely brought Red 5 up out of the swamp in Empire... Just so happens to be a Palpatine which woopdie doo, solves that little problem of why she is so crazy powerful in the first place. It's an easy out for a mistake made a few years ago in TFA.

Oh.. And don't forget the perfect timing and decision making events summed up as "A feeling". And the power of friendship being driven home like a nail in your own coffin.

This sequel trilogy was a mistake from the beginning. I knew it would be from the moment it was announced.

I am very butthurt. Rightfully so.

snippet.textDisplay: Really disappointed in your opinion on critics. I grew up on StarWars (originals first),I am a die hard fan. While I can still find things to enjoy about The Force Awakens and Rise of Skywalker, I truly believe JJ Abrams did a terrible job with his movies. After years of being “distant” from StarWars, it was Rian Johnson’s The Last Jedi that truly reinvigorated my love for StarWars. I read the books/comics, watch the shows, and play the games. Everyone has their opinion about the The Last Jedi and you are all entitled to whatever you believe. But you must admit this, Rian Johnson was not afraid to take risks, that in my opinion, turned out fantastic. Everyone was disappointed with how Luke was portrayed. My question to you is this, since the old EU was cancelled out and labeled as Legends, what do you truly know about Luke? It has been 30 years since Return of the Jedi, you do not know everything that made him that way. It was Yoda that brought his old self back and I love that. JJ Abrams focuses too much on fan service and is truly afraid to take risks. The only movie since Disney took over that performed fan service well was Rogue One. I saw the Rise of Skywalker and I literally rolled my eyes about a dozen times at the ridiculous fan service. But aside from that, the second half of the movie, which would supposedly feature one of the greatest space battles on StarWars history, was cinematically boring. We got a split second here and there of what was going on but no real chance to soak it in like other movies. As far as the story goes, I can deal with it, y’all must understand that WE are NOT the writers of this trilogy so if we don’t get what we want, whether it’s in the Last Jedi or Rise of Skywalker, we must come to terms with that because it isn’t going away.

snippet.textDisplay: It's fine that you don't like The Last Jedi, it wasn't what you expected and it made you mad or it betrayed what you thought the characters or story should be. The movies like any other piece of art or story can be interpreted different ways by different people. What you take away from a story might not be what I take away from it, but that doesn't mean we both can't be inspired or entertained by it. I think you're forgetting or just choosing to ignore that it was The Last Jedi that brought "your hero" Luke Skywalker back. At the end of that movie he realized that he was wrong by leaving, he was wrong to step away even though he failed. By showing up to face down the First Order with his laser sword at the end of that movie he was allowing the one last light of hope for the galaxy "The Resistance" to not be snuffed out on that day. I know it was a force projection, but it was still a hero's sacrifice because it killed his physical body to save his friends. That's my way of interpreting it and I hope it doesn't sound like I'm attacking your opinion of that character or movie. If that's how it sounds I'm sorry. But I don't think we should be able to just throw away The Last Jedi or ignore it. Just like a lightsaber needs to be shown more respect than what Rey showed it by throwing into a fire, so do all the people that worked so hard on The Last Jedi. It's as much a part of the story now as all the other movies.

snippet.textDisplay: There are a lot of problems still, its is 1000% better then the other 2 but still, the leia scenes in the beginning with random dialog abou underestimating droids felt like it was put in there bc they still had a prerecorded line of it they used for leia to get screen time. Furthermore apart from all the story telling flaws in the beginning, i absolutely disliked how few casualties there were on the 'goodguys' side "they're just... Civilians" yeah and they destroyed a fleet of planet killing supers ships full of trained military personnel with bizarrely low casualties. It felt too easy. Also, no one of significance died (save for leia) at any given point during the film: chewie - > NOPE different transport she couldnt tell he was on standing 20ft away from it, when she could sense him in a ship in the upper atmosphere from the planet surface? Chewie's death wouldve outraged fans but would provide interesting character development to rey who now learns the consequences of the darkside she leant into. The girl on kijimi who gives Poe her free pass off the planet (which was apparently essential) was not on kijimi anymore in the few hours it that took place before all of it got blown to bits eventhough it took her years and years to try and get off it, as stated in the movie but managed now in hours when she gave her only hope away... Finn gets surprisingly force sensitive during the movie btw. Apart from that they did truly redeem themselves in alot of ways. A LOT OF WAYS. They tried to draw up parallels with earlier movies in the moments you said didnt make much sense or were slightly confusing. You also didnt mention kylo entering the sith temple blaster in hand in a style of running reminiscent of han solo. Kylo-rey power scaling fix was huge plus. Didnt like that they dropped anakin from the movie in like force ghost form. Also ben and han moment: han isnt transparent (aka not a ghost) as ben states: "you are just a memory" its him telling himself to be true to himself but projects his father onto that role he isnt real. 3 hour movie, there's a lot to talk about, i sont think it was great, but is was certainly good. Better than 8 and 1 for sure lot of stuff i liked (incl. Imoroved stormtrooper aim) and things i disliked. But a great redemption effort

The girl on kijimi who gives Poe her free pass off the planet (which was apparently essential) was not on kijimi anymore in the few hours it that took place before all of it got blown to bits eventhough it took her years and years to try and get off it, as stated in the movie but managed now in hours when she gave her only hope away... Finn gets surprisingly force sensitive during the movie btw. Apart from that they did truly redeem themselves in alot of ways. A LOT OF WAYS. They tried to draw up parallels with earlier movies in the moments you said didnt make much sense or were slightly confusing. You also didnt mention kylo entering the sith temple blaster in hand in a style of running reminiscent of han solo. Kylo-rey power scaling fix was huge plus. Didnt like that they dropped anakin from the movie in like force ghost form. Also ben and han moment: han isnt transparent (aka not a ghost) as ben states: "you are just a memory" its him telling himself to be true to himself but projects his father onto that role he isnt real. 3 hour movie, there's a lot to talk about, i sont think it was great, but is was certainly good. Better than 8 and 1 for sure lot of stuff i liked (incl. Imoroved stormtrooper aim) and things i disliked. But a great redemption effort
